{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":8605,"record_hash":"sha256:e2e3af7167853f0676a323ff9b680fc3970b3ccab7b17a0522d688c2820151c4","timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:12:23.444Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, it’s weird. Your instinct is right.\n\nIt’s there for one reason: `git_meta_lib::Session::open(repo_path)` creates/opens `.git/git-meta.sqlite` and runs migrations. That means even a `--dry-run` can create or mutate GitMeta state. The SQL path is the workaround that lets dry-run read existing dedupe state without writing anything.\n\nSo:\n\n- Is SQL needed for normal capture? No.\n- Is SQL needed for strict `--dry-run reads existing state but writes nothing` with the current GitMeta API? Basically yes.\n- Is it ideal inside `gitmeta.rs`? Not really. It leaks GitMeta’s private SQLite schema into our crate.\n\nThe cleaner version would be one of these:\n\n1. Best: add/read a GitMeta API like `Session::open_read_only_existing()` upstream, then delete all SQL here.\n2. POC-pragmatic: move the SQL into a tiny private module like `gitmeta_readonly.rs` with a comment saying it exists only until GitMeta exposes a read-only API.\n3. Smallest code: keep it as-is, accepting the ugliness because it is scoped to dry-run.\n\nMy preference: option 2. It doesn’t make the feature bigger conceptually, but it stops `gitmeta.rs` from looking like it owns GitMeta’s database schema.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:12:23.444Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}